Questions.Question: How distracted or focused are you when you are learning new things with other people?

synonym.name: Disruptive
synonym.action: You aren't paying attention. You  also distract others to draw attention away from your own inattention. You would not be able to recall any details from this situation.

synonym.name: Distant
synonym.action: You aren't paying attention. You  also distract others to draw attention away from your own inattention. You would not be able to recall any details from this situation.

synonym.name: Unwitting
synonym.action: You are paying some low level of attention to the learning process, but overall, your mind is elsewhere. You are oblivious to most of what is going on around you. You are not particularly preoccupied by anything and you aren't disruptive to others. You struggle to recall many details of what you've learned, however.

synonym.name: Ignorant
synonym.action: You are paying some low level of attention to the learning process, but overall, your mind is elsewhere. You are oblivious to most of what is going on around you. You are not particularly preoccupied by anything and you aren't disruptive to others. You struggle to recall many details of what you've learned, however.

synonym.name: Forgetful
synonym.action: You drift in and out of attention. You get distracted easily. You struggle to stay focused on what you are learning. You can recall some details, but you struggle on information relating to specific or specialised topics.

synonym.name: Scatter-brained
synonym.action: You drift in and out of attention. You get distracted easily. You struggle to stay focused on what you are learning. You can recall some details, but you struggle on information relating to specific or specialised topics.

synonym.name: Receptive
synonym.action: You are open to taking in new information and you are focused on what you are learning. You find it easy to recall both specific and general information later.

synonym.name: Open
synonym.action: You are open to taking in new information and you are focused on what you are learning. You find it easy to recall both specific and general information later.

synonym.name: Zero on In
synonym.action: You are paying attention, but your level of attention is actually distracting to others as you are trying to take control over what you are being taught.

synonym.name: Monopolise
synonym.action: You cannot tolerate any interruption to what you are doing. You become frenzied in your attention and engagement. You may hound the teacher or try to dominate and show off your level of knowledge.

synonym.name: Consume

synonym.name: Risk-Averse

synonym.name: Imrpoving

synonym.action: You can fall into a negative spiral and think that "everything" is going wrong and "nothing" ever goes right. You may think that things will "never" get better and you may forget that you haven't always felt this way.

synonym.name: Catastrophise
synonym.action: You resign yourself to the situation as you feel too afraid of failing to do anything about it. You feel negative and critical about everything and you can catastrophise situations and believe that they are worse than they actually are.

synonym.name: Lack of Perseverance
synonym.action: There is contemplation and desire to change, but there is also a lack of perservance, a comparison to others (which can lead to resentment), and an avoidance of self-imposed obstacles.

synonym.name: Brave
synonym.action: You believe in yourself to get through this. You don't engage in negative or catastrophic thinking. You don't feel sorry for yourself. You practice gratitude and know that everything passes eventually.

synonym.name: Adaptable
synonym.action: You believe in yourself to get through this. You don't engage in negative or catastrophic thinking. You don't feel sorry for yourself. You practice gratitude and know that everything passes eventually.

synonym.name: Romanticise
synonym.action: You fake positivity while minimising your feelings about the situation. You suppress your feelings but do not acknowledge the impact of the situation on yourself.

synonym.name: Overdo
synonym.action: You exaggerate the positives of the situation and are slightly out of touch with reality. You tend to overdo positive thinking and romanticise and over-emphasise situational aspects.

synonym.name: Overdo

synonym.name: Fanciful
synonym.action: You draw away from and refuse anything that is at odds with your opinions. You have idealistic and unrealistic expectations which don't have chances of being realised. It can lead to despair and burn out.
